##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
,
  "PGcourse.pl",
);



##############################################

$fname = RandomVariableName(type=>function);

Context("Numeric");

$coef= non_zero_random(2,10,1);
$f = Formula("$coef*x");
$a = random(1,5,1);
$b = random(-5,-1,1);
$c = 0;

Context("LimitedNumeric");
$ansa = Compute($f->eval(x=>$a));
$ansb = Compute($f->eval(x=>$b));
$ansc = Compute($f->eval(x=>$c));


##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Evaluate the function [`[$fname]`] at the given values.


    [`[$fname](x)=[$f]`]


a. [`[$fname]([$a])=`] [________________]{$ansa}
b. [`[$fname]([$b])=`] [________________]{$ansb}
c. [`[$fname]([$c])=`] [________________]{$ansc}


END_PGML



##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

To evaluate a function like [`[$fname]`] at a certain value, say at [`[$a]`], we substitute [`[$a]`] in for [`x`] in the function's formula:

a. [`\begin{aligned}[t][$fname]([$a]) &= [$coef]\cdot[$a]\\
                                      &= [$ansa]\end{aligned}`]

    Similarly, we have:

b.  [`\begin{aligned}[t][$fname]([$b]) &= [$coef]\cdot[$b]\\
                                      &= [$ansb]\end{aligned}`]


c.  [`\begin{aligned}[t][$fname]([$c]) &= [$coef]\cdot[$c]\\
                                      &= [$ansc]\end{aligned}`]


END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();

